nd":"England"},"en":{"1120–10 September 1198":"1120–10 September 1198","1120–1198":"1120–1198","–Female":"Deceased","1150–Male":"1150–Deceased","1100–1169":"1100–1169","1104–Female":"1104–Deceased","1104":"1104","1169":"1169","1100":"1100","1198":"1198","1120":"1120","before 1150":"before 1150","10 September 1198":"10 September 1198","1150":"1150","30 May 1169":"30 May 1169","London,London,England":"London, England, United Kingdom","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Ely, Cambridgeshire, , England":"Ely, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Richard FitzNeale was born in 1120, in Ely, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Bishop Neal \"Nigel\" of Ely Le Poer, was 20 and his mother, Maud Mistress of Neil Nigel Ramsbury, was 17. He married Mrs Richard FitzNeale before 1150, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died on 10 September 1198, in London, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 78."},"et":{"1120–10 September 1198":"1120–10. september 1198","1120–1198":"1120–1198","–Female":"Surnud","1150–Male":"1150–Surnud","1100–1169":"1100–1169","1104–Female":"1104–Surnud","1104":"1104","1169":"1169","1100":"1100","1198":"1198","1120":"1120","before 1150":"enne 1150","10 September 1198":"10. september 1198","1150":"1150","30 May 1169":"30. mai 1169","London,London,England":"London, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Ely, Cambridgeshire, , England":"Ely, Cambridgeshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England"},"fi":{"1120–10 September 1198":"1120–10. syyskuuta 1198","1120–1198":"1120–1198","–Female":"Kuollut","1150–Male":"1150–Kuollut","1100–1169":"1100–1169","1104–Female":"1104–Kuollut","1104":"1104","1169":"1169","1100":"1100","1198":"1198","1120":"1120","before 1150":"ennen vuotta 1150","10 September 1198":"10. syyskuuta 1198","1150":"1150","30 May 1169":"30. toukokuuta 1169","London,London,England":"London, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Ely, Cambridgeshire, , England":"Ely, Cambridgeshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"England"},"fr":{"1120–10 September 1198":"1120–10 septembre 1198","1120–1198":"1120–1198","–Female":"Décédée","1150–Male":"1150–Décédé","1100–1169":"1100–1169","1104–Female":"1104–Décédée","1104":"1104","11